                      "name": "sr1",
                      "descendants": {
                        "hzWga": {
                          "content": "Volume I"
                        },
                        "o9qy1o": {
                          "content": "Part 1 · Chapter 2"
                        },
                        "cBZj5": {
                          "content": "The Surrounding Light (Ohr Makif) does not enter the vessel — it remains outside until the vessel is corrected. The study of TES draws this surrounding light closer to the student."
                        }
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "rK3G6",
                      "type": "ref",
                      "ref": "M4Iex",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "name": "sr2",
                      "descendants": {
                        "hzWga": {
                          "content": "Volume I"
                        },
                        "o9qy1o": {
                          "content": "Part 2 · Chapter 5"
                        },
                        "cBZj5": {
                          "content": "The surrounding light reforms the vessel by illuminating from afar. It is called 'surrounding' because it encompasses the vessel from outside, waiting for the appropriate correction."
                        }
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "wM5po",
                      "type": "ref",
                      "ref": "M4Iex",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "name": "sr3",
                      "descendants": {
                        "hzWga": {
                          "content": "Volume II"
                        },
                        "o9qy1o": {
                          "content": "Part 1 · Chapter 3"
                        },
                        "cBZj5": {
                          "content": "When the vessel achieves sufficient correction through the surrounding light's influence, it becomes capable of receiving the inner light in equal measure to what the surrounding light has invested."
                        }
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "M3Gk1w",
                      "type": "ref",
                      "ref": "M4Iex",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "name": "sr4",
                      "descendants": {
                        "hzWga": {
                          "content": "Volume III"
                        },
                        "o9qy1o": {
                          "content": "Part 1 · Chapter 1"
                        },
                        "cBZj5": {
                          "content": "Both inner and surrounding lights originate from the same Infinite Source. The difference lies only in their relationship to the vessel — one fills, the other illuminates from without."
                        }
                      }
                    },
